data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 and require **no migration**.

That said, the code would benefit from modernization using `Task`/`Parallel.ForEach` instead of raw threads:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
        {
            Thread.Sleep(100);
            item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
        });
    }
}
```

This is simpler, uses the thread pool efficiently, and supports `CancellationToken` if you need cancellation later — but it's an improvement, not a required migration step.
